segments.text: Now the second.
You remember going to your first football game as a student?
Oh, I do indeed.
What was a football game weekend like?
It's what you live for in 1976, Haskell.
Our football fortunes had changed dramatically from those days when I accompanied my father up here in the late 60s and early 70s.
So much so that in 1976, we were ranked in the top 25 and regarded as a real power, defensively particularly, and favored in most of the games that we played.
We were playing Kansas State in the fall of 1976,
And it was well over 100 degrees at 1 o'clock in the afternoon.
Most of our games kicked off at 1 o'clock.
Incredibly humid, bright, sunshiny day.
And I had a date.
And in those days, you just didn't go to a football game with a date without buying her a mum, an Aggie mum.
Quite a tradition.

And it was almost a package for a weekend that if you had a date to the game, you almost had to figure out what you were going to do on Friday night, Saturday morning, the game, and then Saturday night.
It wasn't just, do you want to go to the game?
It was quite a dilemma to figure out, you know, what are we going to do Friday night and Saturday and, you know.
But it was also great anticipation.
What did you all do on those nights?
We tried to find someplace you could go eat dinner and go to a movie.
There weren't many choices for either.
You do it like you do now.
In a lot of ways, you'd find a group of people and go somewhere and eat and then do a movie, and it was all building up to obviously the Midnight Yale practice.
And the big question was, you know, when the lights go out, this is your first date.
Are you gonna kiss this girl for the first time in Kyle Field?
You know, and you did on occasion.

And then on Saturday you'd buy the mum and meet her parents or she'd meet yours or something and go to the game together and stand three and a half hours and then have to decide if you needed to shower before you went out or whether or not you were just going to go out right after the game.
Where did the out of town young ladies spend the nights?
I don't know, really, because I don't remember ever dating a girl other than a girl that came up from Laredo who stayed with another girl in a dormitory.
But most of the time I didn't have that.
And you had a car.
I did.
So that getting around wasn't a problem.
Correct.
I didn't access that car Monday through Friday most weeks.
And if you were on midnight yell practice, it was actually held at midnight, and what did students do after midnight yell practice?
Where'd you go?
The International House of Pancakes and Taco Bell were the two most prominent

hangouts after midnight Yale practice and I think some of it had to do with the amount of beer that you'd had that evening or what have you because it seemed to promote a level of an appetite that you just had to go cater to at 12 45 or one o'clock.
I can remember at Taco Bell standing in line for over an hour
But it was almost a secondary party because the parking lot at Taco Bell would be just a gathering of four, five, 600 Aggies.
And was it normal to ask a girl for a date for the whole weekend?
Yes, indeed it was.
I think that was just an expectation.

Now I did have a roommate that thought that was the case for him, and on a tough weekend and I had to console him, he found out that no, she had just agreed to go to the game with him and that was it.
No Yale practice, no Friday night, no Saturday night, no lunch before the game, no nothing.
Do you remember any examples of somebody that you knew?
that went to yell practice with a young lady who did not know about the kiss.
Yeah, I do.
In fact, she had been told about it and didn't believe it.
And I guess thought it was just some more of this Aggie lore that she had heard about.
She was from Austin.
And her date was rather shy and quiet about telling her about this tradition, but the rest of us were not.

And on Friday night we kept telling her, that was one thing that Aggies love to do and they'll always love to do, is talk about the traditions at A&M and what's going to happen and how great it is to march in behind the band and lose your shoes and when the lights go out you better be ready.
I guess she didn't think that it was going to happen, but we marched in behind the band.

I don't remember her losing a shoe, but the lights went out and this shy, rather reserved young 19-year-old boy grabbed her and she bought into it for a few seconds and then collected herself and said, wait a minute, I didn't agree to that.
But it was rather fun.
Then on Saturday morning what was the routine?
The routine was always sleep late, hang around the dorm, talk about the game, figure out if you didn't have a date what you were really going to do, but if you did have a date

you had to plan your day because, believe it or not, mums sometimes were sold out by 11 a.m. And I can remember going somewhere and finding somebody that was selling mums on some street, coming back to the dorm and putting them in the refrigerator, and then taking them with me to go pick up my date.
It was kind of an interesting situation when you had a

date who lived on campus and you know on a real hot day you wouldn't go get your car to drive over to Mosier Hall so I can remember hauling that mum across campus and by the time I arrived at Mosier Hall you know just being hot and sweaty and my mum being almost wilted
And here I am just ready to go on a date.
But that was just part of it.
By the 70s, was the number of coeds beginning to be large enough that the typical Aggie who was looking for a date was quite often able to get one?
I wouldn't say quite often, but certainly able.
And I also would say that a lot of guys
still had high school sweethearts that came to A&M, you know, on weekends.
But yeah, I'd say you could find a date pretty easily.
Later in the year, were we still bringing Tessies up on the train or the bus?
No.
That had ended.
That had ended.
And let's see, what did we, was it Aggie Sweetheart?
So that had terminated.
Going home to Laredo, was there any routine or any ritual about giving rides to guys and signing up and so forth?
Yeah, there was.
Because Laredo was such a long way and there were so many cities en route, it was quite often the case that a guy from San Marcos, New Braunfels,
San Antonio, Pearsall, Divine, Cthulhu, and Laredo of course wanted a ride.
And that was not a problem at all.
Most of the time it was a Laredo person because that's a long trip and not the gas expensive
Was it normal for them to share?
Yes.
Oh, yes.
Yes, it was.
But I didn't go home a lot, to be honest with you.
I enjoyed deer hunting.
I enjoyed Thanksgiving.
But other than a lot of buddies saying, why don't we go to Laredo this weekend, I didn't necessarily feel the need to go home.
Do you remember any, in your first year here, do you remember any significant out-of-town trips for anything other than home?
Oh yes, oh yes, yeah.
A lot of away games.
We'd go to Baylor and U of H and Rice, a lot of the old Southwest Conference venues.
That was always popular.
We'd always load up and have a road trip.
I distinctively remember in the fall of 1978,
when a lot of us had just gotten our rings, we made a road trip to Houston.
We were playing rice and one of our Houston dorm buddies was having a party at his house.
And in a caravan leaving town near Navasota, we started launching aluminum cans at each other, empty aluminum cans.
It was quite popular to just roll down your window about four inches and put the open end of the empty
aluminum can in the window.
And when you'd flick the switch or roll it down another quarter of an inch, the suction would catch it and just jettison it.
And when that got to be too laborious, it was just quicker, easier, and sometimes more accurate to throw a can at a friend's car.
I remember Mark Martin, Class 79,
Volkswagen Beetle in the car ahead of us, throw in that can, and the look on his face, he was just in the other lane, just went stark white.
Because here came the can, and I didn't see it, but right behind it apparently was his Aggie ring.
And about when we pulled over, they pulled over, and we all, two cars backed up, but within an hour
Haskell, there were probably 15 cars pulled over because we had to find his Aggie ring.
And I'm going to guess there were 45, maybe 50 people on that median looking for an Aggie ring, which we found.
All right.
Your mention of Aggie rings, describe your feelings and so forth when you got your ring.
Great anticipation.
Excuse me.
I had thought about staying at A&M for summer school when I ordered my ring, and I did not.
My college roommate from Lake Jackson who was a scene cadet talked to me about a course that we had both had trouble with at A&M that was offered at Laredo Junior College and would transfer.
So he suggested that we both go to Laredo Junior College that summer.
We did, and we had a big time.
We lived in a little garage apartment at our house and went to Laredo Junior College.
But that summer is when I got my ring.
And it was rather unceremonious in nature because I ordered it in the spring and it came in a box at home in the summer.
And it was just me.
It was delivered and there it was.
Do you remember anybody you proudly showed it to first?
Oh, just everybody.
My mother was the first one I showed it to.
My dad knew that I'd gotten it in a phone call and then he came home and, of course, I think that was a very proud moment for him.
What did it cost?
It cost $110 and then $2.50 to ship it to Laredo.
Have you since then had any Aggie ring stories where you lost a door?
Yes.
I worked for Hughes Tool Company when I graduated from A&M selling rock bits in the oil field.
And in Brenham, Texas on a very cold, cold January day in 1980,
I looked down while I was jetting up a rock bit on a Clayton Williams' own rig, I might add.
My ring was not there.
And in the great expanse of a location, as they're known for an oil drilling site, I had no idea where that ring was.
But I couldn't have been more fortunate.
The company man
for Clayton Williams was indeed an Aggie, class of 64, I think.
And he didn't exactly shut the rig down, but any able-bodied person that was not on duty
was assigned to find that ring.
And we never found it that day, but the next day I drove up on location and one of the rig workers said, you need to go to Mr. Johnson's trailer, he's got something for you.
And I knew exactly what it was.
And there it was, he'd found my ring.
All right, do you have any ring stories about it being recognized somewhere far away?
Yes, yes I do.
And I don't remember the fellow's name, but it was when I was field director, and this is a great story.
It was a young Aggie who was with one of the big oil companies, and he was assigned to the Middle East as a last-minute assignment.
And typically, I understand, you go through some kind of orientation to the Middle East culture when you're permanently assigned there.
He was somewhat of a fill-in.
And it wasn't a bar, but it was some type of coffee tea house.

restaurant i'm not sure and the only reason this female was in there is that she was the daughter of the proprietor and normally apparently not a lot of females would frequent this place without some reason such as their spouse or whatever they didn't go in there on their own but this was a rather apparently attractive younger female
And my friend made her acquaintance and tried to engage her in conversation.
She did not speak English, but he thought she was attractive and that maybe she would go out with him.
And the father caught wind of this and watched it, and within a matter of minutes, police were hauling him out of the establishment.
And he didn't know what was going on.
All he tried to do was talk to this young lady.
He'd been there all of about 24 hours.
Well, he put up resistance, and as he got to the door and they were hauling him out, he threw his arms against the jams of the door.
And they pulled his left arm, and his raggy ring was on his right hand, and he held on and he swept the door jamb as they hauled him out.

Fortunately his ring made noise and he made noise and one of the patrons in the establishment saw that hand and saw that ring and within an hour or so was at the police station or whatever it was and was taking care of him and it was a
high-ranking official with Aramco, who was a fight in Texas Aggie.
And he said, son, I'm here to get you out, but let me explain a few things to you about the Middle East.
And so I thought that was an interesting Aggie ring story.
As far as you're aware, what other institutions have as much tradition about rings as A&M?
None to our level, Haskell.
None to our level.
And I have great familiarity with that.
But I would have to admit that there are those such as the service academies or even the Citadel that take great pride to the extent that
maybe 100% of those eligible do order and wear class rings.
That was never the case in the Southwest Conference.
It's not the case with most major institutions.
It's just not a coveted keepsake.
As far as I'm aware, the academies, VMI Citadel, maybe Clemson,
A few Ivy League-type schools, both in the East, maybe Stanford, a little bit Rice, I think, and so forth.
But I think most other schools have let it slip badly.
Let's see.
Did celebrities who came to visit the campus while you were here, any famous people?
Yes.
Ronald Reagan came here on a campaign swing in the fall of 1979.
I shook his hand in the MSC.
I told him I was going to vote for him, that I hoped he became president of the United States.
Steve Martin, the comedian, came here, and I happened to just be standing somewhere when he just walked right by me.
And it was on the east side of G. Raleigh White.
I didn't know who he was.
He was dressed in a T-shirt and blue jeans.
What did he describe him physically?
He was about my height and had gray hair and
I wouldn't have known it was him if he hadn't said hello.
Guess what?
His hometown, Waco.
Is that right?
Doesn't fit, does it?
No, I didn't know.
He doesn't seem like my impression of Waco.
Linda Ronstadt came here when I was a freshman, and I thought that was big time.
But I'd have to say that my biggest celebrity, or the guy that I remember the most, was Bob Hope.
Came here on a Friday night before a home football game, and I had a date to it.
And I remember Tom Wilson presenting
Bob Hope with an Aggie jersey that had 12 on it, and that was a big deal.
Was this in G. Raleigh?
Yes, it was.
Describe a basketball, an Aggie basketball game.
Oh, yes.
Can I call you back?
Okay, thank you.
Those were frenzied atmospheres in the days of, oh I don't know, whatever G. Raleigh accommodated, seven, eight thousand, nine thousand maybe for basketball.
It helped that we had a very successful program and that we'd won the Southwest Conference I think in 75 and in 76 before I got here.
But a ticket to a home basketball game was really a premium around here.
And sometimes, even with a sports pass, you lined up two hours before a game, you read the battalion, and you did not throw it away.
Because in my junior year, a group of us started just by default, once again, a tradition that I hope still carries on of reading the battalion
while the opposing team is being introduced.
We didn't have necessarily a basketball band, we had the full band in G. Wally White.
So the atmosphere was not only frenzied, it was loud, it was interactive with the team, everybody knew who everybody was, it was just a great atmosphere.
What did you guys think about our coach then?
Oh, we loved him.
Everybody loved him.
He was one of us.
You know, he wasn't Dr. Shelby Metcalf.
He was an Aggie and related well and just always had time for people.
Great guy.
And you all didn't make any noise during the game.
Oh, gosh, no.
No, we were quiet as church mice, but no.
Indeed, we did.
Do you remember going to Silver Taps?
Yes, I do.
Bond recollections.
What was your impression the first time?
Well, it was one of, this is why I came here.
This galvanizes my feelings about A&M.
I didn't know any of the deceased.
I think there were three kids or four kids, car accident victims.
I didn't know any of them, but it didn't matter because at 10-15 everybody in Moore Hall was turning out lights and going to silver taps.
Everybody.
Nobody was going to stay behind because they had to study, or they were on the phone with their parents or their girlfriend.
Lights were out, and if you tried to stay back, you had some challenges, no matter what your reasoning was.
Did you go to Muster as a student?
I did, oh yes, very much so.
Describe Muster in those days.
Moving, but not... Where was it held?
In G. Raleigh-White.
I don't remember it just being an all-inclusive, got to go to Muster.
Silver Taps was more the emotional commanding activity.
Muster was more, if I don't have anything else to do, I'll go.
It just didn't have the, for me at least, or for the dorm atmosphere, it didn't have the anticipation, the buildup that, you know, at 5.30 we got to be in G. Raleigh for Muster.
And Bonfire, describe it and any activities you and your buddies.
Well, I worked on Bonfire.
Bonfire was much like it is today, an anticipated semester-long activity.

There were some times when if you didn't necessarily have the familiarity with the culture of Bonfire, you could have been ostracized a little bit because you didn't respect the perimeter or the red pots or the
the protocol that they assigned to the bonfire that given day or that week, whether it was push or what have you.
There was a lot of animosity in my days regarding bonfire between the band and the Red Pots and the yell leaders.

As to who ceremoniously was in charge of yell practice the night Bonfire burned, because the Red Pots had built it, and the band was marching around Bonfire, but yet the yell leaders took center stage.
So it was kind of a triumvirate.
Now where was it held?
On Duncan Field.
And what did you, did you work on it your first year?
I did.
I had no choice.
In Moore Hall at about my first experience with bonfire was an axe handle on my door saying, get up or else and let's go.
And where was the cutting area, do you remember?
Just south of Navasota, just on the other side of Navasota towards Houston.
And you as a newcomer, were you treated like a fish in bonfire?
No, I was treated like a frog, which is worse.
Okay.
Which is worse.
And so your part was to help cut?
Yes, sir, and I had to wear a white piece
adhesive tape on my blue jeans, and I pinched my left finger and almost broke my right finger.
Did indeed break it.
But great camaraderie, you know, a great cause, it seemed like.
We were there for, you know, once you got into it, you took great pride in it.
The fall of 76 is what I regarded as my bonfire, technically.
About when in the fall did you all start working on it?
About the first week school started, actually, we had a bonfire crew chief in our dorm, and we had a meeting about the second week of school and told us all about bonfire and what it meant.
And so during a typical week, how much time did you spend?
Not hardly at all.
More on Sunday mornings.
Sunday morning.
Sunday morning was a significant cut day and then evening Sunday afternoon was a day you worked on Bonfire.
It wasn't an everyday deal.
How many weeks before Bonfire did you and your buddies get to quit working in the cut area?
Probably about a month out, about the middle of October, something like that.
And the stack, I never worked on the stack.
Was there, in the cutting area, were there both civilian and corps students?
Oh, indeed there was, yes.
And people may argue with this, but there was a female who actually was in the cutting area when I was there.
And so what did you and your friends think about that?
What were your feelings as the bonfire was ignited?
Well, mine were generated by a lot of pride in the fall of 76 because I had my girlfriend from Laredo up here.
I had friends who had gone to other schools visiting and a friend from the University of Texas was over here.
Bonfire was two days before the game that year because we were playing in Austin.
my first bonfire.
And so these people came up and then we went home to Laredo.
But I felt like more of a host and in showing off this magnificent bonfire to friends and family.
So it was tremendous pride.
What are the events and or activities that contribute significantly to Aggie spirit?
Haskell, I'd have to point back again to, unfortunately, maybe tragic situations that bring Aggies together.
Silver taps, I'd say, had more of an impact on me.
When people ask the question,
You know, what does it mean to be an Aggie?
I suspect there's 245,000 variations of that.
But I'd also have to recall hundreds, maybe thousands, of speeches I've heard when people go to a podium and say something and then refer to it.
That's what being an Aggie is all about.
To me, being an Aggie is about one thing and one thing only, pride.
Now, your interpretation of what makes up that pride is certainly open for individual interpretation.
But to conclusively say that's what being an Aggie is all about, I'd have to say pride is the only word that comes to my mind.
And I was proud of my fellow Aggies when I went to Silver Taps, that everywhere you look, there's Aggies.
Are there some other activities and or events that contribute to that pride?
Oh, I think there are indeed.
I think Aggies helping Aggies is a tradition that's never promoted.
It's not one that shows up in a handbook.
It's not one that anybody refers to as a distinct tradition, but it underlies
every tradition we have.
I think the old adage about Aggies hiring Aggies is probably somewhat accurate.
But I really believe that the camaraderie that came from our military background manifested itself into a tradition of Aggies just help Aggies.
That's just what you do.
They're family.
And if you've got a ring and somebody else got a ring, that's an instant bond.
And all those things that go with what being an Aggie means to them.
But ultimately, I want to say that summarily it's pride.
As you look back, what did A&M do for you as a student that proved to be significant for you later?
You'll find this interesting, I hope.
When I came to A&M in the fall of 1976,
I was a relatively shy introvert.

Although I'd been involved on a very limited basis in high school and particularly with my Future Farmers of America involvement, I was not one to get into everything and join clubs and run for office and so on and so forth.
I think what A&M did for me was establish a level of self-esteem, self-confidence, a level of involvement.
It's what I talked about when we first started this interview.
It was an atmosphere of welcome.
You're expected to be involved, and no matter what you have to contribute, get involved.
It served me well because when I graduated from A&M I was not necessarily shy, but I'd overcome a lot of that introvert nature.
I think one of the big concerns today ought to be the worry about
how today it may be easy for a kid to go off by him or herself and not get involved in anything.
No doubt about it.
When you consider 30,000 plus students who live off campus, that's a legitimate concern.
Yeah, yeah.
In those days, as you said, you
There was no way you could have avoided certain things.
Let's see, some Aggie indulgences during that day.
What did the typical student drink or smoke?
I didn't run around with anybody.
